Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Pop the @diced butternut squash{1} onto a large (lined) #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste}, season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until soft and golden, ~{18-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into small pieces.

Roughly chop the @parsley{5%g}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Halve the @chilli{1/2}(halved lengthways, deseeded and finely chopped). Double for 4p.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1}(grated) using a #garlic press{} or by hand.

Halve the @lemon{1}(halved).

Add @water{1%L} to a #medium pot{} over high heat. Bring to the boil.

To make your stock, add the @Hello Muscat{1%sachet}, stir to dissolve and reduce heat to lowest setting.

Place a separate #large pot{} over medium heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

When the oil is hot, add the onion and @Irish bacon lardons{100%g}. IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Cook bacon thoroughly.

Stir and cook until the onion is soft and the bacon is browned, ~{5-6%mins}.

Add the garlic and chilli (use less if you don't like spice) and cook for ~{1%min} more.

Add the @risotto rice{225%g}, stir and cook until the edges of the rice are translucent, ~{1-2%mins}.

Stir in a ladle of your stock. When the stock has been absorbed, stir in another ladle.

Keep the pot on medium heat and continue stirring in stock, letting it absorb each time. The cooking time should take ~{25-30%mins}.

Once cooked, remove from the heat (your risotto will be ready when the rice is al dente—cooked through but with a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle).

Add the roasted butternut squash, the @grated Italian style hard cheese{50%g}, three-quarters of the parsley and a knob of @?butter{to taste} if you have any.

Stir to combine.

Add a squeeze of lemon juice, taste and add more if desired.

Serve the bacon and butternut squash risotto in #bowls{}.

Finish with a sprinkling of the remaining parsley.